value_old: A pathologic tract that connects an opening in the anal canal to the perianal skin. In the vast majority of cases there is a history of perianal abscess.
value_new: An intestinal disorder characterized by an opening in the anal canal to the perianal skin. In the vast majority of cases there is a history of perianal abscess.

value_old: Autosomal dominant dopa-responsive dystonia (DYT5a) is a rare neurometabolic disorder characterized by childhood-onset dystonia that shows a dramatic and sustained response to low doses of levodopa (L-dopa) and that may be associated with parkinsonism at an older age.
value_new: An autosomal dominant dopa-responsive dystonia in which the cause of the disease is a variation in the GCH1 gene.

value_old: Pseudohypoaldosteronism type 1 (PHA1) is a primary form of mineralocorticoid resistance presenting in the newborn with renal salt wasting, failure to thrive and dehydration.
value_new: A rare, primary form of mineralocorticoid resistance characterized by mild to profound salt wasting either restricted to the kidney (renal pseudohypoaldosteronism type 1), or generalized affecting many organs (generalized pseudohypoaldosteronism type 1). Clinical presentation is in the neonatal period with failure to thrive, vomiting and dehydration with biochemical findings of hyperkalaemia, metabolic acidosis and, elevated plasma aldosterone and renin concentration.

value_old: Any early infantile epileptic encephalopathy in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the DNM1 gene.
value_new: Any developmental and epileptic encephalopathy in which the cause of the disease is a heterozygous mutation in the DNM1 gene.
An inherited susceptibility or predisposition to developing epidermodysplasia verruciformis.
A postpartum condition consists of persistent lactation and amenorrhea in patients not breast feeding.
Any developmental and epileptic encephalopathy in which the cause of the disease is a homozygous mutation in the DNM1 gene.
